text: I understand that he has good opinions on product quality, but sometimes.... sometimes he just makes content with thoughts
He has some valid points. Not all, naturally, but he’s not completely wrong either.
I guess it's the click bait titles that people love these days
It’s his thesis statement, though. It is the core of his argument.
under what conditions does he say it failed?
Their original stated purpose of the product was to get needed reprints for Modern. Today Modern decks are over a thousand dollars and so much of these masters sets are full of cheap bulk rares.
The fact that they suck
:kappa: :stuck_out_tongue:
Vs full of actually played and needed cards.
He says WotC emphasizes draft in these sets too much which, especially given the price to draft, works against the stated goals.
There can’t be controversy if nobody ever starts any controversy.
Some of us messy queens live for the drama.
Again, he has a point.
He doesn't understand finance and he should keep his dumb opinions to himself once in awhile
BOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOM
Don't ask, I just really wanted to do that
To be fair, I don't get MTG finance at all.
Sure, but that’s a tough sell to most users who don’t understand the nature of MTG finance. All they see are the $10 draft packs they open with <$1 worth of value.
Meanwhile dealers are busting Masters packs by the case
They have to to get the few Chase rares.
It’s a perception problem that WotC stays mum on, so populous rhetoric will keep the natives riled up.

They doubled the number of Tarmogoyfs out there and the price didn't tank. You have any idea how hard that is? They perfectly threaded the needle and all they hear is some failed English professor bitching that some packs have bulk rares? Gtfo
I’m pretty sure the only thing that would satisfy the Professor and a few others is for WotC to have a singles market
But that likely means they still haven’t met demand.
The nature of increasing the number of Goyfs increases demand
<@U32LRG9NU> is right on the money, I'd have been really excited and really sad had I opened a goyf, I'd had wanted to build a modern deck with it, but I'd need 3 more...
Only so long as the demand remains constant.
But for every Goyf/Aether Vial/constructed staple someone pulls from a pack, they still need 3 more
So you triple the demand every time someone opens one
If a person with 0 goyfs opens a Goyf, they need three more Goyfs
There is a leveling off point...but they haven’t reached it. Modern has grown in popularity so the demand grows with it.
I gave a mouse a cookie once too. Wouldn’t recommend it. Mice are ungrateful bitches
If you give a mouse $100k, it will bitch that boosters are $10
To be clear, I’m not on board with the Prof, but his points resonate because the actual issues are difficult to explain to a mass audience.
I wish I had both 10 and 100k
Most people are dumb, it's not surprising that most people agree with him when he's wrong
Just scoffing that people are stupid isn’t right either.

I remember a dude on Twitter was raging at me because I said ornithopter masterpieces were still a good thing and he was bitching that it would only be a $20 masterpiece when it could have been a sol ring masterpiece instead. Then ornithopter masterpieces are like, $80 or whateve r
I write articles and podcast where I make persuasive arguments
That's all I can do

So to play this game the expectation is that the average player has to be so invested that they have to dig to get the subtleties of MTG finances that really affect the price of the cards they want to get?
But this isn’t your problem to solve, it’s WotC’s.
And MaRo is always going on about what's intuitive for players, etc. Granted mtg finance may not be within his purview.
He admits it isn’t.
But that could also be a front to prevent those questions on his Tumblr.
Modern also instead intuitive for new players. Neither is edh. That’s why we have brawl and standard
Modern isn’t for new players, so saying new players need access to modern staples is disingenous
I actually don't want most people to grasp the subtleties of finance. I want them to shut up about finance
Magic is an incredibly expensive game. They can’t ignore such a core piece of the experience.
